stylometry: Transportation problems is a problem used to determine a minimum shipping cost. There is a specific number of products that must be shipped from the origin, and the destination must receive a specific number of products. Transshipment problems are more complex transportation problems. The idea is still the same, to minimize profits; however, nodes, arcs, and flows are used. A node is a point on a network. An arc is the pathway between nodes. And a flow is the shipping of items from node to node through an arc. Transshipment problems ship from an origin to a destination as well; however, warehouses can also be a part of the flow. A product may be shipped from an origin, to a warehouse, and then finally to the destination. An example of a transshipment problem is shipping cars. Origins may be Ohio, Pennsylvannia, Georgia, and Florida, but there may be warehouses in North Carolina and Virginia. Destinations might be Texas and New Orleans. The point of the transshipment problem is to minimize the cost of shipping. This may be done by either sending cars directly from an origin to a destination, such as Ohio to Texas, or possibly shipping to a warehouse first, such as from Ohio to North Carolina, and then North Carolina to Texas.
